  "title": "Inverse Trigonometric Functions",
  "description": "Study the principal value branches, properties, and graphs of inverse trigonometric functions.",
  "chapters": [
    {
      "id": "principal-value-branches",
      "title": "Principal Value Branches",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "To make trigonometric functions invertible, we restrict their domains to ensure they are one-one and onto. These restricted domains define the principal value branches."
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Principal Value Branches:"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "sin⁻¹x: Domain [-1,1], Range [-π/2, π/2]",
            "cos⁻¹x: Domain [-1,1], Range [0, π]",
            "tan⁻¹x: Domain R, Range (-π/2, π/2)",
            "cot⁻¹x: Domain R, Range (0, π)",
            "sec⁻¹x: Domain R-(-1,1), Range [0, π]-{π/2}",
            "cosec⁻¹x: Domain R-(-1,1), Range [-π/2, π/2]-{0}"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "component",
          "name": "InverseTrigUnitCircle",
          "props": {}
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "properties",
      "title": "Properties",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Inverse trigonometric functions satisfy several important properties that are useful in simplifying expressions and solving equations."
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Reciprocal Relationships:"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "sin⁻¹(1/x) = cosec⁻¹x for x ≥ 1 or x ≤ -1",
            "cos⁻¹(1/x) = sec⁻¹x for x ≥ 1 or x ≤ -1",
            "tan⁻¹(1/x) = cot⁻¹x for x > 0"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Symmetry Properties:"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "sin⁻¹(-x) = -sin⁻¹x for x ∈ [-1,1]",
            "cos⁻¹(-x) = π - cos⁻¹x for x ∈ [-1,1]",
            "tan⁻¹(-x) = -tan⁻¹x for x ∈ R"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Complementary Relationships:"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "sin⁻¹x + cos⁻¹x = π/2 for x ∈ [-1,1]",
            "tan⁻¹x + cot⁻¹x = π/2 for x ∈ R",
            "sec⁻¹x + cosec⁻¹x = π/2 for |x| ≥ 1"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "graphs",
      "title": "Graphs",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "The graphs of inverse trigonometric functions are obtained by reflecting the graphs of corresponding trigonometric functions in the line y = x."
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Key Characteristics:"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "Graphs of sin⁻¹x and tan⁻¹x are increasing functions",
            "Graph of cos⁻¹x is a decreasing function",
            "All inverse trigonometric functions are continuous in their domains",
            "tan⁻¹x and cot⁻¹x are defined for all real numbers",
            "sin⁻¹x, cos⁻¹x, sec⁻¹x, and cosec⁻¹x have bounded ranges"
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
  "quiz": {
    "title": "Inverse Trigonometric Functions Quiz",
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": 1,
        "text": "sin⁻¹(0) = ?",
        "options": [
          "a) π/2",
          "b) 0",
          "c) π",
          "d) -π/2"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": "b",
        "explanation": "sin⁻¹(0) = 0 because sin(0) = 0 and 0 is in the principal range [-π/2, π/2]."
      },
      {
        "id": 2,
        "text": "If cos⁻¹x = π/3, then x = ?",
        "options": [
          "a) 1/2",
          "b) √3/2",
          "c) 1",
          "d) 0"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": "a",
        "explanation": "cos(π/3) = 1/2, so if cos⁻¹x = π/3, then x = 1/2."
      },
      {
        "id": 3,
        "text": "Principal value of tan⁻¹(-1) ?",
        "options": [
          "a) -π/4",
          "b) 3π/4",
          "c) π/4",
          "d) -3π/4"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": "a",
        "explanation": "tan(-π/4) = -1 and -π/4 is in the principal range (-π/2, π/2)."
      },
      {
        "id": 4,
        "text": "sin⁻¹x + cos⁻¹x = ?",
        "options": [
          "a) π",
          "b) 0",
          "c) π/2",
          "d) π/4"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": "c",
        "explanation": "This is a complementary relationship: sin⁻¹x + cos⁻¹x = π/2 for all x ∈ [-1,1]."
      },
      {
        "id": 5,
        "text": "Graph of y = sin⁻¹x lies between:",
        "options": [
          "a) [0, π]",
          "b) [-π/2, π/2]",
          "c) (-π/2, π/2)",
          "d) [0, π/2]"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": "b",
        "explanation": "The range of sin⁻¹x is [-π/2, π/2], so the graph lies between these values."
      },
      {
        "id": 6,
        "text": "tan⁻¹x + tan⁻¹y = π/4 when?",
        "options": [
          "a) (x+y)/(1-xy) = 1",
          "b) x + y = 1",
          "c) xy = 1",
          "d) x - y = 1"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": "a",
        "explanation": "Using the addition formula: tan⁻¹x + tan⁻¹y = tan⁻¹((x+y)/(1-xy)) = π/4, which means (x+y)/(1-xy) = tan(π/4) = 1."
      },
      {
        "id": 7,
        "text": "sin⁻¹(-1/2) = ?",
        "options": [
          "a) π/6",
          "b) -π/6",
          "c) 5π/6",
          "d) -5π/6"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": "b",
        "explanation": "sin(-π/6) = -1/2 and -π/6 is in the principal range [-π/2, π/2]."
      },
      {
        "id": 8,
        "text": "If θ = cos⁻¹x, then sinθ = ?",
        "options": [
          "a) √(1-x²)",
          "b) -√(1-x²)",
          "c) 1-x²",
          "d) x²-1"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": "a",
        "explanation": "Since θ = cos⁻¹x, we have cosθ = x. Using the identity sin²θ + cos²θ = 1, we get sinθ = √(1-cos²θ) = √(1-x²). Since θ ∈ [0,π], sinθ ≥ 0."
      },
      {
        "id": 9,
        "text": "Which is NOT true?",
        "options": [
          "a) sin⁻¹(-x) = -sin⁻¹x",
          "b) cos⁻¹(-x) = π - cos⁻¹x",
          "c) tan⁻¹(-x) = π - tan⁻¹x",
          "d) tan⁻¹x + cot⁻¹x = π/2"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": "c",
        "explanation": "tan⁻¹(-x) = -tan⁻¹x, not π - tan⁻¹x. The correct relationship is tan⁻¹(-x) = -tan⁻¹x."
      },
